  "prompt": "What are ductile materials?",
  "response": "Ductile materials are those that can be plastically deformed or stretched into thin wires without breaking when subjected to tensile stress. Key characteristics of ductile materials include:\n\n1. Properties:\n- High capacity for plastic deformation\n- Ability to undergo significant strain before fracture\n- Good tensile strength\n- High elongation percentage\n\n2. Common examples:\n- Metals like copper, aluminum, gold, silver\n- Some steel alloys\n- Platinum\n- Nickel\n\n3. Microstructural characteristics:\n- Typically have face-centered cubic (FCC) crystal structures\n- Contain many slip planes that allow easy dislocation movement\n- Possess good grain boundary characteristics\n\n4. Advantages:\n- Can be drawn into thin wires\n- Easily formed and shaped\n- Resist sudden failure\n- Good energy absorption capabilities\n\n5. Applications:\n- Electrical wiring\n- Jewelry making\n- Construction materials\n- Mechanical engineering components\n- Electrical transmission lines\n\n6. Contrast with brittle materials:\n- Brittle materials fracture with little plastic deformation\n- Have limited ability to undergo permanent shape changes\n\nDuctility is an important property in material selection for various engineering and industrial applications.",
